Ok, given that you want them to operate from a factual basis, the only FACT of god's existence you could substantively argue is the fact of our existence.  The bibble itself you cannot take because it was written by men with man's purposes behind it 335 years after JC was supposed to have walked the earth.  It is rife with self-contradiction, and as you say, there is stuff in it you don't want to believe.  There is no evidence that the War Santa had anything to do with its creation, codification, or distribution.  It was a political standardization by Emperor Constantine to secure his rule over the 'holy' roman empire.  Are you going to burn in hell for wearing jeans and wool socks?  The bibble calls this a sin (cotton + wool) among other ridiculous things.  Constantine's editing was so offensive, it broke the council of nicea and several members ended up exiled.<br>
<br>
You assume 2 givens (I do not agree with, but will argue from for this debate.)  <br>
1.) There is a god.<br>
2.) It created everything.<br>
<br>
Given the evidence there is a creation, does it support or contradict the bibble?  God is unforgiving.  The weak are regularly killed and eaten by the strong.  Why would god need to intervene for your sick child because you pray when he already hand crafted their immune system and provided all that was needed to repair them?  No medical technology today does anything more than assist our natural healing process.  It is truely amazing and worth praise, weather god built it or not.  Our knowledge pales in comparison to the feats of evolution (started by god?) that brought us to where we are.  <br>
<br>
You want to operate from facts, yet believe (eg 'feel') that god is real.  This is self-contradictory.  There may indeed be a god, no one can prove there isn't (you cannot prove a negative) but once a positive assertion is made (such as a religion or bibble) it can be disproven.  Keep your faith, believe in god all day long.  Do good works, feel pride in your merits as a decent human, but give yourself the credit for your actions, for they are your own.  God does not meddle in our daily lives.  The bibble is political gibberish, not gods work.  The human body, the rocky mountains, the sun and stars may be, but the bibble isn't.<br>
<br>
This is deism.  It was the (predominant) religion of our founding fathers despite the modern inclination at historical revisionism to the contrary.  I can choose not to beleive in god, you can choose to, it doesn't affect reality either way, but as soon as you say he talks to you, people call you crazy.<br>
