<br>
I have to agree with DBC about the Catholic church. I remember sitting in my world history class in high school thinking, &quot;How can anyone learn about the history of the Catholic church and still believe it is inspired by God?&quot; Each king changed parts of it in order to fit his agenda. Because the rule was so based in the church, the best way to influence laws was by changing the Bible. I believe, and I may be wrong, but I believe that is the reason LDS say that they believe in the Bible as long as it is translated correctly. <br>
<br>
Also, any leader of any church living on the earth today is merely a mortal man (or woman in some) who is fallable. As are all of us. No matter what or who you believe in, we are all trying to negotiate life. We are all seekers of truth whether truth be the big bang, evolution, God, Jesus Christ, etc. <br>
<br>
Heather, unless you have seen Jesus Christ or God with your own eyes you are still basing your religion on your feelings. Even if you did see God, you would have to believe that it was God either because he told you so (debatable because anyone could say they are God) or because you in some way felt/believed said person was really God. Either way, you have to go with what your head and heart say is true. <br>
<br>
Even in the example of the court case and basing your decision on facts.... that is simplistic or we would have no need for any jury in any court. You have to make decisions about the facts that are placed in front of you. We all come from different experiences and different ideals, beliefs, etc. You can take 12 people on a jury and have each and every one of them interpret the facts differently even though they were all presented the exact same facts in the exact same courtroom at the exact same time. The truth is that there are very few things that just &quot;are&quot; and are the same to every person. It is our perceptions of the world that make up the facts to us. So, to say that you base belief in God or belief in there being no God on facts is in the argument fallable. <br>
<br>
Both the Bible and the Book of Mormon if pulled apart and placed scripture against scripture can be proved contradictory. The truth is that different situations warrant differences. It is illegal to shoot someone unless you are defending yourself, they intrude into your home with intent to harm you or your family, etc. There are very few ABSOLUTES. Just as there is a commandment that thou shalt not kill, the same God who gave the commandment allows us to defend our families. The commandment of thou shalt not steal... if someone took something that belongs to you and they then take ownership of it and you go get it back, are you then stealing from them? Who on this earth is to decide EXACTLY what God meant by every scripture? The only way I can see to determine if you are on the right track, assuming you believe in God, is to pray and ask Him if what you believe is true. Heather, do you believe that God doesn't answer your prayers? If so, why do you pray to Him? Why would He want you bugging Him if He had no answer for you? If God does answer prayers (which I believe He does), how do you get your answer? Because the last time I checked, God does not have email, he doesn't have a postal address and he isn't sending postcards to answer your questions. The only way we can get the answers to our prayers is to listen and the answers can only come in the form of feelings or in the form of events that we feel/believe are an answer to our prayer. <br>
<br>
The whole idea that you cannot trust your feelings just proves that you too can't trust your beliefs because you have no proof... only the fact that you believe the Bible is true. And that belief is based on your feelings and thoughts (also fueled by feelings). Just as your belief that Mormons are evil and that Satan has every last one of them in his grasp by deceiving them into believing that the Book of Mormon is true is based on your feelings and perceptions. You have no proof of that except your interpretations (feelings) about what you believe the Bible (also feel that it is true) tells you. So how do you explain other people perceiving and interpreting the Bible differently than you? Are you closer to God than they? Does God tell you that everyone else is wrong and you are right or do you just assume that your feelings and thoughts about each scripture is the truth even though others perceive those same verses differently. <br>
<br>
The other thing I wonder about is why people who are not of the LDS faith find the LDS church so intimidating that they will spend countless hours trying to disprove it, write articles about why it is wrong, spend time that could be spend doing good and spend it trying to trash another persons perceptions and beliefs about what is true. Why is that? I've just always wondered about that....<br>
<br>
